VERNON
Onto the very reason we're all here today.
GFX6: STAND BY YOUR MEN
It's International Men's Day and a chance to open up the conversation about men's mental health - and sadly the stats say it all.

Every day, 12 men take their own life by suicide, and it remains the biggest killer of men under 50.

We've all been forced to confront our mental health like never before over the past two years, 
and now, even the toughest men in the world, 
are being trained to open up about their feelings.

I was invited to the Royal Marines training centre in Lympstone 
to chat to the man in charge of training up commandos - 
Colonel Simon Chapman OBE -  
and I found out how they're dealing with mental health in the forces. 

Before we talk about how WE open up, 
let's have a look at what I learned.

CARD FOR VERNON / PART 3 / MENTAL HEALTH IN PANDEMIC 

* Just over 3 out of 4 suicides (76%) are by men

* Suicide is the biggest cause of death for men under 35

* Men aged 40-49 have the highest suicide rates in the UK

* 12.5% of men in the UK are suffering from one of the common mental health disorders

* Men are nearly three times more likely than women to become alcohol dependent

* Men are less likely to access psychological therapies than women: only 36% of referrals to NHS talking therapies are for men.

body:
CARD FOR VERNON/ PART FOUR/ STAGES OF A RELATIONSHIP
The merge - The honeymoon phase as you fall in love.

Doubt and denial - You finally start to notice your differences, and find that the same qualities that once seemed so perfect have begun to annoy you.

Disillusionment - The power struggles in the relationship have come fully to the surfacea and issues the couple have swept under the carpet are now glaringly obvious.

Decision - You're at breaking point, having arguments, wanting alone time, and perhaps even contemplate ending the relationship.

Wholehearted love - You've made it through the tough times, and your relationship is at its healthiest and most rewarding.
